June 23=2C 2025

Question: Hasn=E2=80=99t the U.S. technically been at war with Iran since=
 1979 (embassy invasion=2C hostages=2C etc.)? What about the War Powers Re=
solution of 1973=2C especially since it seems to hit the middle ground you=
 say is needed? Why not include that in your discussion?

Response:
The problem with the War Powers Resolution is that it violates the constit=
utional mandate that Congress must pass a declaration of war before war ca=
n be waged. The Constitution makes no mention of another way the U.S. migh=
t go to war=2C nor does it define war=2C so we must take it that the frame=
rs were speaking of war as it is commonly understood: armed conflict betwe=
en nations. By allowing military engagement without a formal declaration=
=2C the War Powers Resolution bypasses this constitutional requirement. Th=
is may be more practical in modern times=2C but Congress cannot legislate=
 around a constitutional imperative. We do not want Congress passing laws=
 contrary to the Constitution=2C such as laws limiting free speech.

I think that the virtue of the declaration of war is that it is a sober an=
nouncement that the nation is at war and that now our lives must take this=
 into account. When a nation goes to war=2C it should galvanize the public=
 and not ooze into it. We have gone into many wars and called them police=
 actions=2C counterinsurgencies=2C peacekeeping and whatnot=2C without pub=
lic acknowledgement that the nation is at war and without presidents and m=
embers of Congress taking full responsibility for their decision. Too many=
 soldiers have died without the sober and public recognition of the nature=
 of what is happening. So for me=2C if the War Powers Resolution is necess=
ary=2C it should be enacted through a constitutional amendment and not as=
 a workaround. Of course=2C that is a complex and painful process and won=
=E2=80=99t happen.
Question: Do you see a fundamental issue regarding the role of special int=
erest lobbying and its ability to shape U.S. foreign policy? The Israeli l=
obby is strong in D.C.=2C and the attack on Iran went against the U.S. int=
erest of pulling out of the Middle East. Also=2C what about the scenario o=
f a president exploiting his war declarations to grow his power. Arguably=
 you can=E2=80=99t rule out power grabs=2C especially by people who have d=
edicated their careers to amassing influence=2C no?

Response:

American political life is constructed so that people can govern. All peop=
le have special interests=2C and frequently those interests do not coincid=
e. So treating the concept of special interests as somehow corrupt seems t=
o me to violate the foundations of democracy. Before both world wars there=
 were claims that special interests were causing us to go to war. Prior to=
 both wars there was an argument that we were siding with the British only=
 because white=2C Anglo-Saxon Protestants wanted to protect the nation the=
y came from. In a democracy=2C all wars are shaped by the passions of the=
 people=2C and the charge by the isolationists was that we had no business=
 giving lend-lease to Britain and thereby bringing us closer to war with G=
ermany=2C a war in which the U.S. had no interest. So special interests ab=
ound in a healthy democracy=2C and there are those who favor war for their=
 favored nation=2C frequently the one their past identifies with. The Germ=
an American Bund fought to keep the U.S. out of the
European war. So it goes. In a nation of immigrants this is not unusual. W=
e are a nation of special interests.

Presidents=2C under the Constitution=2C do not declare war; Congress does.=
 The president is commander of the armed forces and fights the war militar=
ily. Presidents in time of war have dramatically increased power over the=
 economy=2C censorship and other things having to do with war. This is why=
 the Constitution does not give the president the authority to start wars.=
 But given that the president is the only one to have been elected by the=
 people as a whole=2C it is appropriate that he have appropriate power in=
 war. He is the trusted representative of the majority of the people=2C th=
rough the Electoral College. One of the problems is that all presidents ar=
e despised by a large group of citizens. This is why it is urgent that the=
 public recognize that any president=2C however much they despise him=2C w=
as democratically elected=2C and to maintain opposition but to not try to=
 delegitimize him.

This is most true in wartime. The Roosevelt haters were many=2C accusing h=
im of being a dictator. When Congress declared war=2C reflecting the publi=
c wishes=2C that hatred didn=E2=80=99t die=2C but it was less apparent bec=
ause of the state of war. In the Vietnam War=2C undeclared by Congress=2C=
 hatred of LBJ was not constrained by congressional action. But then I don=
=E2=80=99t know if Congress would have been willing to declare war on Viet=
nam. It was Congress that failed to block JFK by refusing to fund the war=
 unless there were a congressional declaration of war. So there are ways f=
or Congress to limit wars if they wish. Actually=2C the Supreme Court coul=
d have blocked him too=2C save that the legal system had failed long befor=
e to block war without a declaration. Yes=2C this is a mess=2C and no=2C I=
 don=E2=80=99t know how to untangle it. Nor do others think it is a proble=
m. So we live with it.
Comment/Question: What role do you think Congress should play (if any) in=
 the decision by a president to go to war? Without congressional approval=
=2C the will of the people is not clearly reflected. Notably=2C the courts=
 have stayed away from deciding the legality of the use of force =E2=80=93=
except for the ruling during the Korean War in 1952=2C when President Harr=
y Truman ordered the seizure of most of the nation=E2=80=99s steel mills t=
o stop labor strikes from shutting down mills that were critical to the na=
tion=E2=80=99s security and war efforts and the Supreme Court ruled it unc=
onstitutional.

Response: I deeply believe that the president should not have the power to=
 go to war without the nation=2C as represented by Congress=2C having the=
 final say. The Vietnam War began with Kennedy sending =E2=80=9Cadvisers=
=E2=80=9D to Vietnam who necessarily engaged in combat. LBJ dramatically i=
ncreased it. The war was unwise and its initiation written off as minor. T=
he war tore the nation apart=2C and we failed=2C costing us 50=2C000 dead.=
 If we recognized that in fact we were engaging in war and put it before C=
ongress and the American people=2C we might have gone there anyway=2C but=
 then the American people would have made the decision and=2C holding ours=
elves responsible=2C as the war grew our rage over it would have been miti=
gated if not eliminated. We must go to war rarely and then with the consen=
t of the governed=2C so the governed carry the responsibility and cost of=
 war. But then again=2C in this age=2C how do we do this?
Comment: There are dangers of a serious call for a constitutional conventi=
on. There are no guarantees for retaining any of the current document=2C n=
o restrictions on what new elements could be introduced=2C and the divided=
 American public may not be able to withstand such a controversial process=
=2E Thoughts?

Response: I agree that a constitutional convention would be a mistake. I p=
ointed to it only to make it clear that we must urgently reconsider how we=
 go to war and that something dramatic must be done=2C but God only knows=
 what emerge from such a convention. At the same time=2C my serious point=
 is that Congress and the president should amend the constitutional clause=
 on war to recognize the changes that have taken place in technology and s=
uch=2C and to make certain that Congress and the American people take resp=
onsibility for going to war. It would make it much harder to engage in war=
s=2C and the world should know from that amendment that the Yanks will com=
e only with the support of the nation. I do not ever want to see another w=
ar like Vietnam=2C where the soldiers are drawn from those who didn=E2=80=
=99t have college deferments or minor defects like bone spurs. I am emphat=
ically and overtly not a pacifist=2C but I want my country to know when it=
 is going to war and take responsibility for winning it.
Comment/Question: Could it be possible that the Iranians wanted their nucl=
ear sites to be destroyed? They weren't secret anymore. It would allow the=
m to save face with their own people=2C whereas if they gave everything up=
 in a peace deal that would be seen as a huge sign of weakness within thei=
r culture. They could ask for sanctions relief =E2=80=93 since the only ob=
stacle to that was their nuclear program =E2=80=93 which would greatly imp=
rove the economy and the regime=E2=80=99s chance of survival. They might b=
e able to move their program to another=2C far more secretive location=2C=
 with the U.S. thinking that it had destroyed the threat. And they could s=
eparate from their proxies=2C since the majority of them were destroyed an=
yway.

Response: I do not think that the Iranians wanted their nuclear facilities=
 destroyed. I don=E2=80=99t think the public would have thought better of=
 them having spent the resources to build a weapon and then standing by he=
lplessly as the facilities are destroyed. The reason that Iran was buildin=
g nuclear weapons was not necessarily to use them=2C but to frighten other=
 countries and show their citizens that they were now a great power. There=
