<strong>Response: </strong></p>

<div>The problem with the War Powers Resolution is that it violates the con=
stitutional mandate that Congress must pass a declaration of war before war=
 can be waged. The Constitution makes no mention of another way the U.S. mi=
ght go to war, nor does it define war, so we must take it that the framers =
were speaking of war as it is commonly understood: armed conflict between n=
ations. By allowing military engagement without a formal declaration, the W=
ar Powers Resolution bypasses this constitutional requirement. This may be =
more practical in modern times, but Congress cannot legislate around a cons=
titutional imperative. We do not want Congress passing laws contrary to the=
 Constitution, such as laws limiting free speech.<br>
<br>
I think that the virtue of the declaration of war is that it is a sober ann=
ouncement that the nation is at war and that now our lives must take this i=
nto account. When a nation goes to war, it should galvanize the public and =
not ooze into it. We have gone into many wars and called them police action=
s, counterinsurgencies, peacekeeping and whatnot, without public acknowledg=
ement that the nation is at war and without presidents and members of Congr=
ess taking full responsibility for their decision. Too many soldiers have d=
ied without the sober and public recognition of the nature of what is happe=
ning. So for me, if the War Powers Resolution is necessary, it should be en=
acted through a constitutional amendment and not as a workaround. Of course=
, that is a complex and painful process and won=E2=80=99t happen.</div>

