                            <strong>Question: </strong><em>Do you see a fun=
damental issue regarding the role of special interest lobbying and its abil=
ity to shape U.S. foreign policy? The Israeli lobby is strong in D.C., and =
the attack on Iran went against the U.S. interest of pulling out of the Mid=
dle East. Also</em><em>, what about the scenario of a president exploiting =
his war declarations to grow his power. Arguably you can=E2=80=99t rule out=
 power grabs, especially by people who have dedicated their careers to amas=
sing influence, no?</em><br>
<br>
<br>
<strong>Response:&nbsp;</strong><br>
<br>
American political life is constructed so that people can govern. All peopl=
e have special interests, and frequently those interests do not coincide. S=
o treating the concept of special interests as somehow corrupt seems to me =
to violate the foundations of democracy. Before both world wars there were =
claims that special interests were causing us to go to war. Prior to both w=
ars there was an argument that we were siding with the British only because=
 white, Anglo-Saxon Protestants wanted to protect the nation they came from=
. In a democracy, all wars are shaped by the passions of the people, and th=
e charge by the isolationists was that we had no business giving lend-lease=
 to Britain and thereby bringing us closer to war with Germany, a war in wh=
ich the U.S. had no interest. So special interests abound in a healthy demo=
cracy, and there are those who favor war for their favored nation, frequent=
ly the one their past identifies with. The German American Bund fought to k=
eep the U.S. out of the European war. So it goes. In a nation of immigrants=
 this is not unusual. We are a nation of special interests.<br>
<br>
Presidents, under the Constitution, do not declare war; Congress does. The =
president is commander of the armed forces and fights the war militarily. P=
residents in time of war have dramatically increased power over the economy=
, censorship and other things having to do with war. This is why the Consti=
tution does not give the president the authority to start wars. But given t=
hat the president is the only one to have been elected by the people as a w=
hole, it is appropriate that he have appropriate power in war. He is the tr=
usted representative of the majority of the people, through the Electoral C=
ollege. One of the problems is that all presidents are despised by a large =
group of citizens. This is why it is urgent that the public recognize that =
any president, however much they despise him, was democratically elected, a=
nd to maintain opposition but to not try to delegitimize him.<br>
<br>
This is most true in wartime. The Roosevelt haters were many, accusing him =
of being a dictator. When Congress declared war, reflecting the public wish=
es, that hatred didn=E2=80=99t die, but it was less apparent because of the=
 state of war. In the Vietnam War, undeclared by Congress, hatred of LBJ wa=
s not constrained by congressional action. But then I don=E2=80=99t know if=
 Congress would have been willing to declare war on Vietnam. It was Congres=
s that failed to block JFK by refusing to fund the war unless there were a =
congressional declaration of war. So there are ways for Congress to limit w=
ars if they wish. Actually, the Supreme Court could have blocked him too, s=
ave that the legal system had failed long before to block war without a dec=
laration. Yes, this is a mess, and no, I don=E2=80=99t know how to untangle=
 it. Nor do others think it is a problem. So we live with it.
